y = \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2 + 1}}
y=\frac1{\sqrt{x^2+1}}\implies y^2=\frac1{x^2+1}\implies x^2+1=\frac1{y^2}\implies x^2=\frac1{y^2}-1=\frac{1-y^2}{y^2}\implies
\implies x=\frac{\sqrt{1-y^2}}y\;\;,\;\;\text{defined for all}\;\;y\neq 0\;.
\;\sqrt{y^2}=|y|\;
\;\pm\;
y=\frac1{\sqrt{x^2+1}}\Rightarrow y^2=\frac 1{x^2+1}\Rightarrow x^2+1=\frac 1{y^2}\Rightarrow x=\pm\frac{\sqrt{1-y^2}}{y}
y\ne0
y = \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2 + 1}}\\ \left(\sqrt{x^2 + 1}\right)^2 = \left(\dfrac{1}{y}\right)^2\\x^2+1-1=\dfrac{1}{y^2}-1\\x^2=\dfrac{1-y^2}{y^2}\\x=\sqrt{\dfrac{1-y^2}{y^2}}\\x=\dfrac{\sqrt{1-y^2}}{y}\\y\neq0
